Main notations:
N – number of complex variables z1, ..., zN in operators; M – rank of GLM R-matrix, i.e. the size of the basis matrices (A.13). M = 1 is called the scalar case; k – integer number used for numeration of identities (and operators);
η – complex variable (constant parameter) entering the shift operators pi = exp(−η∂zi); ~ – complex variable (constant parameter) entering quantum R-matrix definition;
Γ – lattice of periods Z⊕ Zτ of elliptic curve;
τ – moduli of elliptic curve C/Γ, Im(τ) > 0;
φ(z) – the Kronecker elliptic function φ(~, z) (1.2)-(1.3);
pi – the shift operator (1.1); pI – product of shift operators (2.2) over subset I ⊂ {1, ..., N}; (I, J) – product (2.1) of φ-functions;
Dk – the Macdonald-Ruijsenaars operators (1.4) or (2.3); H – vector space H = (CM )⊗N ; R~ij(z) – R-matrix, i.e. an element of End(H) acting on i-th and j-th tensor components of H; Rij and R − ij – short notations for R ~ ij(zi − zj) and R ~ ij(zi − zj − η) respectively; R̄ij – R-matrix normalized as in (1.11)-(1.12); Pij – the matrix permutation operator (A.21) permuting tensor components in H; −→ N∏ j=1 Rij and ←− N∏ j=1 Rij – the arrows mean the ordering −→ N∏ j=1 Rij = Ri1Ri2...RiN and ←− N∏ j=1 Rij = RiNRi,N−1...Ri1; RI,J and R ′ I,J – the products of R-matrices (2.5) and (2.8) respectively; Dk – the (anisotropic) spin operators (1.14) or (2.17).
